00:13:08.496 --> 00:13:10.156 A:middle
Next, let's talk
about Device Motion.

00:13:12.626 --> 00:13:16.016 A:middle
As you're all aware,
Device Motion APIs have been

00:13:16.016 --> 00:13:18.076 A:middle
on the iPhone since iOS 5.

00:13:18.906 --> 00:13:22.086 A:middle
With watchOS 3, now we are
bringing the exact same APIs

00:13:22.296 --> 00:13:23.716 A:middle
to the Apple Watch.

00:13:26.096 --> 00:13:30.036 A:middle
With the Apple Watch, we have
a very capable sensor package

00:13:30.036 --> 00:13:32.436 A:middle
that is at a fixed
location on our wrist

00:13:32.686 --> 00:13:34.316 A:middle
and we use it throughout
the day.

00:13:34.716 --> 00:13:37.616 A:middle
And because we use our
hands for almost everything

00:13:37.616 --> 00:13:41.036 A:middle
that we do throughout the day,
it's a really powerful tool

00:13:41.036 --> 00:13:42.946 A:middle
to observe all of
that user activity.

00:13:43.936 --> 00:13:46.806 A:middle
And what Device Motion does
is it takes the samples

00:13:46.806 --> 00:13:49.726 A:middle
from the accelerometer and
the gyroscope, and it fuses it

00:13:50.136 --> 00:13:53.326 A:middle
to give you a very clear picture
of all of that user activity,

00:13:53.456 --> 00:13:55.466 A:middle
and all of this right
on your wrist.

00:13:57.166 --> 00:14:00.546 A:middle
All of that motion at wrist
is described by Device Motion,

00:13:57.166 --> 00:14:00.546 A:middle
All of that motion at wrist
is described by Device Motion,

00:14:00.636 --> 00:14:04.386 A:middle
using four distinct
properties: Attitude, gravity,

00:14:04.686 --> 00:14:07.426 A:middle
rotation rate, and
user acceleration.

00:14:09.686 --> 00:14:14.206 A:middle
If you want to know in depth how
these properties are derived,

00:14:14.206 --> 00:14:16.746 A:middle
and how they behave, I
encourage you to go check

00:14:16.746 --> 00:14:20.326 A:middle
out these sessions
from 2011 and 2012.

00:14:20.656 --> 00:14:23.846 A:middle
In this talk though, I'll be
giving you a very brief overview

00:14:23.846 --> 00:14:27.176 A:middle
of this property so that we can
build some infusion and go look

00:14:27.176 --> 00:14:31.086 A:middle
at some examples of how you
can apply them in some health

00:14:31.086 --> 00:14:33.166 A:middle
and fitness apps in
interesting ways.

00:14:34.316 --> 00:14:36.326 A:middle
The first property is attitude.

00:14:37.676 --> 00:14:42.266 A:middle
Using attitude in your apps,
you can get an observation

00:14:42.316 --> 00:14:44.616 A:middle
of the orientation
of device and space.

00:14:44.906 --> 00:14:46.916 A:middle
And when you use CMDeviceMotion,

00:14:46.916 --> 00:14:49.726 A:middle
you get these three
representations of attitude.

00:14:50.496 --> 00:14:54.426 A:middle
As Quaternion, rotation
matrix, and as Euler angles.

00:14:55.426 --> 00:14:57.786 A:middle
Whenever you are using
attitude within your app,

00:14:57.786 --> 00:15:01.726 A:middle
one thing to note is every
single attitude observation is

00:14:57.786 --> 00:15:01.726 A:middle
one thing to note is every
single attitude observation is

00:15:01.726 --> 00:15:04.776 A:middle
going to be relative to
a fixed reference frame.

00:15:05.986 --> 00:15:10.176 A:middle
What this means is every single
orientation observation is going

00:15:10.176 --> 00:15:11.686 A:middle
to be observed from a point

00:15:11.686 --> 00:15:13.536 A:middle
that is not fixed to
the device itself.

00:15:13.536 --> 00:15:17.036 A:middle
So the reference frame remains
static while the device can move

00:15:17.036 --> 00:15:19.396 A:middle
around, and that's
how you observe

00:15:19.396 --> 00:15:20.926 A:middle
orientation-using attitude.

00:15:22.516 --> 00:15:26.196 A:middle
And furthermore, when
your app registers

00:15:26.286 --> 00:15:27.806 A:middle
to start receiving the updates,

00:15:27.936 --> 00:15:30.916 A:middle
that is when the
reference frame is set.

00:15:30.916 --> 00:15:33.396 A:middle
And so every subsequent
sample that you receive

00:15:33.396 --> 00:15:36.286 A:middle
within your app is going
to be computed using

00:15:36.576 --> 00:15:39.046 A:middle
that relative reference
frame that was set

00:15:39.046 --> 00:15:40.426 A:middle
at the start of updates.

00:15:40.786 --> 00:15:43.766 A:middle
So this is something that
you need to kind of be aware

00:15:43.766 --> 00:15:46.146 A:middle
of when you use attitude
in your apps.

00:15:46.586 --> 00:15:48.906 A:middle
And so that you don't
make assumptions

00:15:48.906 --> 00:15:52.476 A:middle
about where the device is
oriented in absolute space.

00:15:53.846 --> 00:15:56.006 A:middle
The next property is gravity.

00:15:57.376 --> 00:16:00.586 A:middle
Gravity is -- well,
it's gravity.

00:15:57.376 --> 00:16:00.586 A:middle
Gravity is -- well,
it's gravity.

00:16:00.586 --> 00:16:02.356 A:middle
It is the force that
is pulling us all

00:16:02.356 --> 00:16:04.426 A:middle
down to the center of the Earth.

00:16:04.426 --> 00:16:06.716 A:middle
And within Device
Motion, it is represented

00:16:06.716 --> 00:16:08.646 A:middle
as a unit vector in
the device frame.

00:16:09.696 --> 00:16:13.366 A:middle
Using gravity, you
can observe the tip

00:16:14.116 --> 00:16:15.726 A:middle
and the tilt of the device.

00:16:17.036 --> 00:16:18.016 A:middle
But you might be wondering,

00:16:18.016 --> 00:16:20.716 A:middle
isn't different tilt also the
orientation just like attitude?

00:16:21.056 --> 00:16:24.206 A:middle
But one key difference is,
now you're observing all

00:16:24.206 --> 00:16:26.776 A:middle
of this orientation
from the device frame.

00:16:27.116 --> 00:16:29.026 A:middle
So take for example, if I were

00:16:29.026 --> 00:16:31.376 A:middle
to hold my hand perfectly
parallel to the ground

00:16:31.376 --> 00:16:35.466 A:middle
to my side, and then I move it
to my front, you won't be able

00:16:35.466 --> 00:16:36.746 A:middle
to observe this using gravity.

00:16:36.746 --> 00:16:39.266 A:middle
Because the x, y, z
components of gravity are going

00:16:39.266 --> 00:16:42.056 A:middle
to remain exactly same
between these two orientations.

00:16:42.056 --> 00:16:45.456 A:middle
To observe something like this,
you need a point of observation

00:16:45.456 --> 00:16:49.326 A:middle
that is external or fixed
while the device is moving.

00:16:49.326 --> 00:16:50.526 A:middle
Which is basically attitude.

00:16:50.526 --> 00:16:53.806 A:middle
So you could use gravity
to observe orientation,

00:16:53.806 --> 00:16:55.706 A:middle
but only in a limited form.

00:16:56.096 --> 00:16:59.036 A:middle
But it might work just
good for the kind of app

00:16:59.036 --> 00:17:01.406 A:middle
that you are thinking of.

00:16:59.036 --> 00:17:01.406 A:middle
that you are thinking of.

00:17:01.586 --> 00:17:03.526 A:middle
One other thing about gravity is

00:17:03.526 --> 00:17:05.816 A:middle
when you hold the
device perfectly still,

00:17:05.816 --> 00:17:07.965 A:middle
you can observe it
using the accelerometer.

00:17:07.965 --> 00:17:09.566 A:middle
It's a constant acceleration

00:17:09.566 --> 00:17:11.036 A:middle
that the accelerometer
will pick up,

00:17:11.496 --> 00:17:14.445 A:middle
and you can read it right
out of accelerometer.

00:17:15.146 --> 00:17:17.876 A:middle
But as soon as you
start moving the device,

00:17:17.876 --> 00:17:19.336 A:middle
now the accelerometer is picking

00:17:19.336 --> 00:17:21.806 A:middle
up not just the gravity
component, but it's also picking

00:17:21.806 --> 00:17:24.195 A:middle
up all of the user-generated
motion.

00:17:24.665 --> 00:17:26.126 A:middle
So it becomes harder and harder

00:17:26.205 --> 00:17:27.896 A:middle
to just get the gravity
component.

00:17:28.556 --> 00:17:31.616 A:middle
What Device Motion does, is
by using sense of fusion,

00:17:31.726 --> 00:17:33.366 A:middle
we switch over to the gyroscope

00:17:33.526 --> 00:17:40.276 A:middle
to start tracking the
gravity unit vector.

00:17:40.276 --> 00:17:42.826 A:middle
Next property is rotation rate.

00:17:43.476 --> 00:17:45.376 A:middle
As the name suggests,
it's the rate

00:17:45.376 --> 00:17:47.146 A:middle
of change of angular motion.

00:17:47.656 --> 00:17:50.636 A:middle
It's very good for observing
something like wrist rotation.

00:17:50.636 --> 00:17:52.396 A:middle
When you are rotating
your wrist,

00:17:52.396 --> 00:17:55.196 A:middle
there is a rotational motion
around the x-axis of the device,

00:17:55.196 --> 00:17:57.556 A:middle
and you can observe that
using rotation rate.

00:17:58.276 --> 00:18:01.146 A:middle
You can also observe any
rotation around the body.

00:17:58.276 --> 00:18:01.146 A:middle
You can also observe any
rotation around the body.

00:18:01.436 --> 00:18:05.566 A:middle
Because most of us, we fix
our torso and we move our arms

00:18:05.696 --> 00:18:08.876 A:middle
so there is going to be some
kind of an arcing motion.

00:18:08.876 --> 00:18:13.016 A:middle
So there is rotation and you can
observe it using the rotation

00:18:13.016 --> 00:18:14.646 A:middle
rate property of Device Motion.

00:18:17.116 --> 00:18:19.966 A:middle
The last of the properties
is user acceleration.

00:18:19.966 --> 00:18:22.406 A:middle
And the user acceleration
that you get

00:18:22.406 --> 00:18:24.706 A:middle
through Device Motion is
compensated for gravity.

00:18:25.216 --> 00:18:28.026 A:middle
Recall how I mentioned
that accelerometer picks

00:18:28.026 --> 00:18:29.416 A:middle
up both the gravity component

00:18:29.416 --> 00:18:30.906 A:middle
and the user-generated
component.

00:18:30.986 --> 00:18:33.206 A:middle
So this is just the
user-generated component.

00:18:33.676 --> 00:18:35.936 A:middle
But it has been compensated
with gravity

00:18:35.936 --> 00:18:39.566 A:middle
that was derived using
device sensor fusion.

00:18:40.776 --> 00:18:44.416 A:middle
So that was a very quick
overview of these properties.

00:18:44.696 --> 00:18:46.866 A:middle
Now let's take a look
at a few examples

00:18:46.866 --> 00:18:48.786 A:middle
of how you can use
them in your apps.

00:18:50.536 --> 00:18:52.786 A:middle
The first property is attitude.

00:18:53.146 --> 00:18:55.116 A:middle
Attitude is very good

00:18:55.116 --> 00:18:57.686 A:middle
for observing any kind
of repetitive motion.

00:18:57.916 --> 00:18:59.536 A:middle
Like rep counting
in weightlifting.

00:18:59.536 --> 00:19:03.536 A:middle
So when you are lifting
weights, you are literally going

00:18:59.536 --> 00:19:03.536 A:middle
So when you are lifting
weights, you are literally going

