through a set of
orientation changes.

00:19:05.756 --> 00:19:09.996 A:middle
So just by looking at how
those orientation changes are

00:19:09.996 --> 00:19:12.006 A:middle
repeating, you can
count the reps.

00:19:12.296 --> 00:19:14.336 A:middle
And the best part about
using attitude for doing

00:19:14.336 --> 00:19:16.656 A:middle
that is now they might
be using a machine

00:19:16.656 --> 00:19:19.846 A:middle
where they're pulling
horizontally or from the top

00:19:19.846 --> 00:19:22.576 A:middle
and you can observe all of
those reps using attitude.

00:19:24.636 --> 00:19:26.746 A:middle
Gravity, as I already
mentioned, it's very good

00:19:26.746 --> 00:19:28.326 A:middle
for measuring tip and tilt.

00:19:28.856 --> 00:19:31.646 A:middle
Which basically means you
can use it in a yoga app.

00:19:32.436 --> 00:19:37.806 A:middle
So if they're doing a downward
dog or holding a warrior pose,

00:19:37.806 --> 00:19:40.706 A:middle
then you can figure out whether
-- how still they're holding it.

00:19:41.076 --> 00:19:43.906 A:middle
And when they're also going
from one pose to another,

00:19:43.906 --> 00:19:46.506 A:middle
you can figure out whether
they're really doing it

00:19:46.506 --> 00:19:48.986 A:middle
in a graceful way, or just
falling over themselves.

00:19:52.686 --> 00:19:57.266 A:middle
One of the most useful ways
of using rotation rate is

00:19:57.266 --> 00:19:59.566 A:middle
to observe the speed
of circular motion.

00:19:59.946 --> 00:20:01.946 A:middle
Take, for example,
a batting cage.

00:19:59.946 --> 00:20:01.946 A:middle
Take, for example,
a batting cage.

00:20:01.986 --> 00:20:04.056 A:middle
So when you are swinging
the bat,

00:20:04.446 --> 00:20:06.856 A:middle
you're not only rotating
your arms around your body,

00:20:06.856 --> 00:20:08.766 A:middle
but there is also the
rotation around wrist.

00:20:09.146 --> 00:20:12.166 A:middle
So you could use both of those
components of rotation rate

00:20:12.166 --> 00:20:13.876 A:middle
to estimate the bat speed.

00:20:14.206 --> 00:20:17.076 A:middle
Of course you'll need to
know how long of a bat it is,

00:20:17.076 --> 00:20:19.806 A:middle
and at what point on the bat
you want to measure the speed.

00:20:22.436 --> 00:20:24.686 A:middle
User acceleration is best used

00:20:24.686 --> 00:20:26.316 A:middle
when there is some
abrupt motion.

00:20:26.716 --> 00:20:30.046 A:middle
Because accelerometer
picks up all of the motion

00:20:30.046 --> 00:20:33.946 A:middle
that the user is doing, if
you try to do some kind of app

00:20:33.996 --> 00:20:35.556 A:middle
